A TypeScript snippet with an interface `Foo` which defines a function `bar`. Immediately afterwards, it defines a class also named `Foo` which implements `Foo` (whatever that means). The `Foo` class defines a method `baz`, but does *not* define a method `bar`, yet this is not an error. Afterwards a new `Foo` is instantiated and `foo.bar()` and `foo.baz()` are called. Neither of these are marked as errors.
A snippet of TypeScript code which includes `class Foo implements Foo`, meaning it's implementing its own interface.

A meme featuring an Elcor alien from the video game series Mass Effect at a computer. The meme is titled "Using conventional comments". The Elcor says in his code review "Passive aggressive: Don't forget to write tests."

Peter Griffin is sitting next to the Christian God in an elevator. The ride is taking a while so Peter makes some small talk by asking "Hey, are deleted files really deleted?" God replies with a sigh "No,they go to the trash." Peter asks a follow-up "What about `node_modules`?" to which God immediately and agrily replies "Gone from the file system forever. Straight to hell. To the boiler room of hell, all the way down." Peter relaxes with relief washing over his face, "Good, good. That makes me happy."

A JavaScript code snippet which defines a Parent class and a Child class which extends it. The Parent class also logs "new parent" in its constructor.

The snippet then logs the output of three expressions.

First, it does `new Child() instanceof Parent)`. This returns `true` and also logs "new parent", reasonable behavior.

Second, it does `Child instanceof Parent`. This returns `false`, also reasonable.

Third, it does `Child.prototype instanceof Parent`. This returns `true` and doesn't log "new parent" at any point. wat?

A screenshot of a TypeScript function called `logOut` which declares a variable `user` and then attempts to initialize it inside a `try` block. It checks two cases, if the user is logged in or if a refresh token is present. If either case is true, the `user` variable is initialized and a `new Error('done')` is thrown, which is caught inside the same function. The `catch` doesn't do anything and merely contains a comment reading "Got a user, stop running the `try` block". Finally, `user.logOut()` is called.

A screenshot of a TypeScript code snippet. This snippet declares a web component named `MyElement` with an optional property named `prop`. Then it creates a new `Document` with `document.implementation.createHTMLDocument()`. With that document, it creates a new `MyElement` and assigns the string 'test' to `prop`. Finally, the snippet appends this element to the main document and logs the value of `prop`. A typical user would expect this to log 'test', however a comment indicates that this line actually logs `undefined`.
